  "text": "The Rust compiler's type inference architecture is centered around three key components:\n\n1. **InferCtxt** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/mod.rs, line 231): This is the main inference context struct that manages the overall type inference engine. The InferCtxt is generic over a lifetime 'tcx and contains the type context (TyCtxt), typing mode, and manages region obligations. It serves as the core infrastructure for type variable unification and constraint solving.\n\n2. **FnCtxt** (compiler/rustc_hir_typeck/src/fn_ctxt/mod.rs, line 44): This is the function-level type checker struct that performs type inference for function bodies, closures, and const blocks. FnCtxt is generic over two lifetimes ('a, 'tcx) and stores function-specific context including the parameter environment (param_env), return type coercion information, and divergence tracking. It wraps and uses InferCtxt for the actual type inference operations.\n\n3. **TypeVariableOrigin** (compiler/rustc_infer/src/infer/type_variable.rs, line 94): This struct defines how type variables are created and tracks their origins. It stores a span indicating where the type variable was introduced and optionally a DefId of the type parameter it was instantiated for. This information is crucial for generating helpful diagnostics when type inference fails.\n\nThe architecture follows a hierarchy: InferCtxt provides the low-level inference machinery in rustc_infer, while FnCtxt in rustc_hir_typeck builds on top of it to provide the high-level function body type checking. TypeVariableOrigin is used throughout the inference process to track the provenance of type variables for better error reporting."
